== Prep ==

Wash and dry all produce. Preheat the oven to 400 degrees.

Halve, peel, and finely dice the @shallot{1}(peeled and finely diced).

Strip the @thyme{1/4%oz} leaves off the stems and roughly chop them.

Trim the ends off the @asparagus{6%oz}.

Peel and medium-grate the @russet potato{12%oz} over a clean #kitchen towel{}. Season the grated potatoes generously with @salt{} and @pepper{}. Toss in half of the thyme. Working over the sink, bring together the corners of the towel and squeeze as much liquid out of the grated potatoes as possible.

== Potato Cakes ==

Heat a drizzle of @olive oil{4%tsp} in a large pan over medium heat.

Place small (approximately 2 Tablespoons) mounds of the potato mixture into the pan and press with a #spatula{} to flatten. Cook for ~{2-3%minutes} per side, until golden brown.

Season with salt and pepper and set aside on a #paper towel-lined plate{}.

== Asparagus ==

Toss the asparagus on a #baking sheet{} with a drizzle of olive oil and season with salt and pepper. Place in the oven for about ~{12%minutes}, until tender.

== Pork Chops ==

In the same pan used for the potato cakes, heat a drizzle of oil over medium-high heat.

Pat dry the @boneless pork chops{12%oz} with a paper towel and season on all sides with salt and pepper.

Add the pork to the pan and cook for ~{2-3%minutes} per side, until browned but not yet cooked through.

Transfer the pork chops and the potato cakes to the baking sheet to finish cooking, about ~{4-5%minutes}.

== Dijon-Shallot Pan Sauce ==

Meanwhile, heat a drizzle of oil in the same pan over medium heat.

Add the shallots and remaining thyme to the pan and cook for ~{2-3%minutes}, until beginning to soften.

Stir @Dijon mustard{1%tbsp}, the @chicken stock concentrate{1}, and @water{1/2%cup} into the pan. Simmer for ~{2-3%minutes}, or until thickened. Season with salt and pepper.

== Finish and Plate ==

Thinly slice the pork chops and serve alongside the asparagus and potato cakes.

Drizzle with the Dijon-shallot pan sauce and enjoy!

> Wringing out the potatoes is the secret to super crispy potato cakes. Don't forget to season your potato cakes while they're still hot!